# Lexicon optimization
- Does Richness of the Base mean anything can be in underlying representations?
    + In theory, yes -- there are no hard limits on URs.
    + For an actual language, no -- learners won't posit "weird" or "crazy" URs without evidence.
- Prince & Smolensky (1993/2004) suggest a learning proceddure called **lexicon optimization**.
    - Basically, the learner only posits URs that deviate from SRs when there is sufficient motivation (such as an alternation).
    + In the absence of such evidence, the UR should match the SR.
    + This runs contrary to the idea that we should minimize the number of underlying sounds in a language.
- Steriade (2007): 
"The idea is that non-alternating phonological properties - say the aspiration of initial [kʰ] in [kʰæt] - are always present in the lexical entry, for the following reason: the right grammar will guarantee the surface occurrence of [kʰ] in [kʰæt] no matter whether [kʰ] or [k] is present underlyingly, but the advantage of the identity mapping /kʰæt/ ➞ [kʰæt] over /kæt/ ➞ [kæt] is that the former avoids a faithfulness violation (Ident [aspiration]). Lexicon Optimization yields (approximately) opposite results on the issue of underlying specification compared to lexical minimality: non-alternating redundant information will always end up lexically listed."








